title: For Sale:  Mosin-Nagant M91/30 Izhevsk
postcontent: This M91/30 is in decent condition, with one piece of wood replaced along the top of the barrel. All three main serial numbers are original and match. Includes shoulder strap, magazine pouches, bayonet, oil can, tool pouch, and a hard case.   The “7, 62 mm Rifle, Model of the Year 1891-30” (more easily referred to as the M91-30) was originally issued to Soviet soldiers in 1930 as an update to the previous Dragoon rifle, with changes including flat rear sights, restamping of sights in meters instead of the now-obsolete arshinii, a cylindrical receiver to replace the octagonal one used previously, and a hooded post front sight instead of a blade sight. Production ran until 1944 at only two arsenals in the Soviet Union- Tula and Izhevsk.   This particular rifle was made at Izhevsk and is the sniper model of M91-30, distinguishable by the bent bolt. Most M91-30s and other rifles of this era would have a shorter, straight bolt, but this would interfere with the PU scopes mounted above it. The bent bolt allowed easy operation without any interference.

title: For Sale:  U.S. Springfield Model 1884 w/ orig. Bayonet & Scabbard & Cartridge  Pouch/ Bannerman
postcontent: PICTURES HERE (over 50): https://imgur.com/a/tcQ2GUp for sale is a U.S. Springfield Armory Model 1884 rifle in .45-70 caliber ( it has come to my knowledge that this is a Bannerman- type Special) with the original blued bayonet (correct) and scabbard. Also the original McKeever cartridge pouch that was issued with this rifle. These are on consignment from the original owner's great grandson (he did not wish to be mentioned so I can't provide the local history). The rifle is in very nice shape. Missing the cleaning rod, but in fine shootable shape with a good bore and rifling. There is pitting in the barrel, but it's not bad for the age. Nice cartouches on the stock and all the markings are very clear and readable. There are over 50 pictures showing every detail inside and out of this package. This would make a great representative instant collection from the Indian War era. Bannerman's and other places bought surplus parts and built rifles apparantly. These rifles can be told by having the "Model 1884' on the receiver. Its a model 1873 as evidenced by the rear sight style and the serial number which dates it to 1875 (an early one!). Also and more importantly, real Springfield 1873s and 1884s for that matter do NOT have a date on the lockplate as this one does. There's no dates on them at all.Read item #9 in this list for more info on the lockplate stamp: http://www.trapdoorcollector.com/FAQ.html$450.00 PLUS ACTUAL SHIPPING or state tax in VT, for the ENTIRE PACKAGE.
